  "prompt": "How would you word \"damas\" and \"chambelanes\" for an english Quinceanera invitation?",
  "response": "For an English Quincea\u00f1era invitation, you can translate \"damas\" and \"chambelanes\" in a way that preserves the cultural significance while making it clear for an English-speaking audience. Here\u2019s how you might word it:\n\n- **\"Damas\"**: \"Ladies of Honor\" or \"Court of Honor Ladies\"  \n  (This reflects the traditional role of the damas as members of the Quincea\u00f1era\u2019s court.)\n\n- **\"Chambelanes\"**: \"Gentlemen of Honor\" or \"Court of Honor Gentlemen\"  \n  (This mirrors the role of the chambelanes as part of the ceremonial court.)\n\nFor example, you could phrase it like this on the invitation:  \n\"Join us as we celebrate the Quincea\u00f1era of [Name]  \nwith her Ladies of Honor and Gentlemen of Honor.\"  \n\nThis keeps the tradition intact while ensuring clarity for English-speaking guests.",
